First-Citizens Bank & Trust Company Key Developments

Randy Martin Joins First Citizens Bank as Director of Private Banking
Jul 13 16
Randy Martin has joined First Citizens Bank as director of private banking. In this role, Martin is responsible for building, growing and managing the company’s private banking business, which provides clients with structured, custom-packaged credit and banking deposit services and access to products that help manage changing interest rates. With 30 years of financial services industry experience, Martin joins First Citizens from Capital One Bank in McLean, Va., where he headed up private banking national underwriting and commercial credit services. Martin currently serves as a member of the panel and the chairman’s committee for the Risk Management Association (RMA) North American Private Lending Roundtable.


The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development Announces Agreement with First-Citizens Bank and Trust Company to Resolve Fair Lending Complaint
Jun 8 16
The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development announced an agreement with First-Citizens Bank and Trust Company, resolving allegations that the bank denied mortgage loans to African American, Latino and Asian American mortgage applicants at a disproportionately higher rate than white applicants. HUD's investigation concerned retail loans originated by the banks predecessor, First Citizens Bank and Trust Co., in 2010 and 2011. HUD filed a complaint against First Citizens Bank and Trust Co. in 2011 after conducting an analysis of 2010 Home Mortgage Disclosure Act (HMDA) data. In January 2015, the South Carolina-based bank was merged into First-Citizens Bank and Trust Company, a North Carolina-chartered commercial lender. As the successor, First-Citizens Bank and Trust Company continued to cooperate with HUD throughout this investigation and ultimate resolution announced. As part of the settlement, First-Citizens agreed to take several steps to ensure and protect equal access to credit including refraining from unlawful consideration of race or national origin when selecting sites for branch offices and services offered, conducting marketing, and defining Community Reinvestment Act assessment areas. In addition, First-Citizens will: Make $140,000 available to nonprofit organizations that provide credit and housing counseling, financial literacy training, and related programs to first-time homebuyers in South Carolina; Adopt a new standardized and objective set of guidelines for a second review of retail channel residential loan applications initially denied by the automated underwriting system; Require all of its employees and agents who have substantial involvement in manual underwriting of mortgages in their retail channel to attend fair housing training; Hire three mortgage banker market specialists that will focus on diverse lending in the Charleston-North Charleston-Summerville, Columbia, and Greenville-Anderson-Mauldin metro areas.


First Citizens Bank Appoints Chris Riley as Commercial Banking Manager for Columbia, Upstate S.C
May 5 16
Chris Riley has returned to First Citizens Bank as manager of commercial banking for the Columbia and Greenville/Spartanburg areas.  He leads First Citizens commercial banking teams for these markets, focusing on developing and managing relationships with local companies. Riley rejoins First Citizens from Regions Financial Corporation, where he most recently served as South Carolina Market President for the past six years. Prior to this, he was Market President at the former Wachovia Corporation in Greenville, S.C., but started the first 14 years of his banking career with First Citizens in North Carolina. He has more than 26 years of banking experience, the last 12 based in the Upstate.


